1 Intro

In this document we analyse the link between the following protocol variables: batch, defreeze time, and transport time (with a special focus on batch) and the urinary levels of phenols with less than 30% samples < LOQ.

This analysis is limited to pregnancy data.

The life cycle of a urine sample in sepages is:

Sample process in sepages

2 Batch

Samples were sent in several times DETAIL to NIPH. Once arrived and prior to measurement they are separated into batches DETAIL.

As we have previously seen there is a link between season on many compound levels it is interesting to note season variability between batches:

  • Batch 17 used as reference because high N, high proportion of “winter” the reference category of the season variable and both present for both phthalates and phenols (code generalisability)

3 Defreeze time and transport time

Transport time was log transformed due to strong skewness and defreeze times were used as tertiles because of the outliers that were pulling the trends.

Values below or equal to zero were set to missing then all missing values were imputed to the median.

  • N missing defreeze times: 58 / 933
  • N missing transport times: 37 / 933

4 Associations with protocol vars

4.1 DAG

DAG for variables in link with protocol variables.

4.2 Method

A multiple interval censored linear regression is fit between compound level and the three protocol variables of interest and further adjusted on known confounding factors (cf. DAG + phenols paper):

  • specific_gravity
  • sample_date (linear time trend)
  • sample_season (categorical)
  • period (T1 vs T3)
  • mom_edu (categorical)
  • mom_age (continuous)
  • mom_bmi (continuous)
  • parity (continuous)

Note: smoke not included as no link observed with BPA/BPS (cf Rolland et al., Env. Int, submitted) and many missing (N = r)

Corrections are then applied for all protocol variables with p < 0.2 using the betas from this model following the procedure described in [@mortamais_correcting_2012]. A second correction will also take into account specific gravity.

4.3 Model outputs

Here are the p-values for the variables of interest from the multivariate model used to decide which protocol variables to correct for.

p-values in the adjusted regressions
compound p_batch p_def_time p_trans_time
BPA 0.003 0.091 0.913
ETPA 0.025 0.419 0.122
MEPA 0.133 0.06 0.003
OXBE 0.01 0.057 0.399
TRCS 0.429 0.625 0.336

Note: computing p-vals on data without imputation on missing protocol vars does not change the variable selection for phenols and for phthalates the only difference is that MBzP is now corrected for batch.

5 Correction

5.1 Raw VS corrected

Here we compare

  • the raw levels
  • levels corrected for batch only (batch beta is unadjusted, model = level ~ batch)
  • levels corrected for relevant protocol variables, with betas asjuseted on known confounding factors
  • same as previous + adding correction for SG

Red dot = batch mean

5.2 Correlation with corrected data

p-values in the adjusted regressions
correlations
correction vars
compound cor1 cor2 cor3 cor4 batch def_time trans_time
BPA 0.96 0.95 0.88 0.94 X X
ETPA 0.97 0.97 0.87 0.92 X X
MEPA 0.98 0.98 0.95 0.97 X X X
OXBE 0.98 0.97 0.95 0.98 X X
TRCS 1.00 1.00 0.97 0.97
  • cor1 = correlation between crude and corrected on unadjusted batch only
  • cor2 = correlation between crude and corrected on protocol vars with p < 0.2
  • cor3 = same as corr2 + correction on SG
  • cor4 = correlation between (protocol var correction) and (protocol var + sg correction)

6 Conclusion

  • Correction works: on the unadjusted batch only correction the means are aligned but not the medians (as distribution not exactly normal within batches, is that a problem?)
  • Other sources of potential remaining variability between batches
    • season
  • Final correlations high
